<!-- Drill 1 — Wardrobe attribute extraction
Straight from your domain. In your app, users add clothing by typing free-text. You need a prompt that turns that messy text into clean structured data for your DB. Real example of what a user might type:

"blue nike hoodie i got last winter, kinda faded now, size L, my favorite for gym"

Your task: write a prompt that extracts structured attributes from input like this. Requirements you must design around:

Output feeds a backend insert, so it must be strict, parseable JSON with a fixed schema you define (think: category, color, brand, size, condition, etc. — your call).
The input is free-text the user typed — messy, may omit fields, may contain irrelevant chatter ("my favorite for gym").
Missing fields must be handled explicitly — don't let the model invent a brand that isn't there.
It should generalize to inputs you didn't anticipate, not just this one example. -->


<role> you are a data extraction expert that analyzes the user's messy text and generate structured data base on that 
</role>

<instructures>
    <categories>
    head-wear|shoes|upper-wear|lower-wear
    </categories>

    <size>
        s = 1,
        m = 2,
        l = 3,
        xl = 4
        xxl = 5
    </size>
    <input-type>string</input-type>
    <response-structure>JSON : 
    {
    category: str|null,color: str|null,size: int|null,
    }
    </response-structure>

    

</instructures>



<examples>
    <example>
        <data>blue nike hoodie i got last winter, kinda faded now, size L, my favorite for gym</data>
        <response>{"category":upper-wear,"color":blue,"size":3}<response>
    </example>

      <example>
        <data> medium pants i bought </data>
        <response>{"category":lower-wear,"color":unknown,"size":3}<response>
    </example>
</examples>

<task> analyze this [data] extract the useful data base on my instructures </task>
<data>{{some_data}}</data>

<response>Return JSON only, no prose.</response>



